However, its tutorial, designed to be completed in five minutes, became a focal point of controversy when professional game journalist Dean Takahashi took over 26 minutes to complete it.

Dean isn’t good at the game, and he self proclaims it in the first line of the review, stating [“I suck at *Cuphead”.* Even going so far as saying “I failed miserably in playing a demo of cuphead”,](https://venturebeat.com/games/the-deanbeat-our-cuphead-runneth-over/) claiming that the video was posted mockingly to poke fun at how bad he was at the game. To his credit, this clip was taken in front of the developers of the game, where most likely having the pressures of the developers watching could lead to much worse gameplay than normal.  

Despite his honesty, the review sparked widespread criticism within the gaming community, igniting a larger conversation about the skill level of game journalists. This wasn’t the only incident to draw scrutiny to game reviewers.  
The Debate Over Difficulty Modes:   

An article released on Kotaku.com Joshua Rivera titled [“An Easy mode has never ruined a game”](https://kotaku.com/an-easy-mode-has-never-ruined-a-game-1833757865?rev=1554244771382) ignited a significant debate within the community. The piece argued that incorporating an easier difficulty setting does not detract from a game’s quality or player experience, especially in games like elden ring or dark souls, where there is only one extremely hard difficulty. The argument many in the community use is that these certain games are designed with a very specific difficulty in mind, creating a direct identity and narrative. They expressed concerns that introducing an easy mode could compromise the intended artistic expression of the developers. But what happens when players such as Dean, with less than appropriate skill, were required to play these difficult games without any easy mode?

## Skill Shapes the Experience:  
It is very easy to see that a reviewer’s skill level in a game influences how they engage with a game, how far they get in a game, as well as the score that they give to the game. For example, a reviewer who struggles with Elden Ring’s notorious challenge could label the game's combat as punishing or unfair, while a more skilled reviewer may praise the combat for its depth. The opposite is also true, reviewers who value skill games may look at childrens games like Spongebob: Battle for Bikini Bottom, and claim that it is lacking challenge or depth. There are also many reviews, such as IGN’s review for Cuphead, that dock the game’s score for being too difficult, even while this is part of the game's intended experience, and has been one of the biggest draws for many gamers. 

## Skill versus Objectivity:   
The real challenge, and one of the main hurdles any good reviewer will need to overcome, is balancing subjective experience with objective analysis. A less skilled journalist needs to be able to separate their frustrations about a game’s design, and realize when struggles they have are due to personal limitation rather than a flaw in the game itself. 

## What to do as a viewer:  
Reviewers will always keep making reviews, some will be good at their games, some will be bad. The majority of reviewers are not going to be as drastic as Dean, but due to the way online forums work, reviewers are incentivised to churn out reviews in extremely short time so their reviews are viewed first and at the top of forums. A journalist’s skill level will impact their review of a game, but this is not necessarily a bad thing. A diverse range of skill among reviewers also shows the diverse range of gamers at home. The key is transparency and the ability to distinguish personal frustrations from legitimate game designs. As a watcher, make sure to take all reviewers into account, as looking at multiple reviews allow for a broader understanding and insight into a game.
